<DIV1 TYPE="sermon">
<PB N="5" REF="009023_0003_1030749A9DA4CA78">
<HEAD>A SERMON, <HI>&amp;c.</HI></HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<Q><BIBL><HI>1 CHRONICLES xxix, 28.</HI></BIBL>
<P>And he died in a good old Age, full of Days, Riches, and Honor; and <HI>Solomon</HI> his Son reigned in his Stead.</P></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>_IN the&s;e Words, we have an Account of the re&s;pectable Circum&s;tances, with which <HI>David,</HI> the <HI>King</HI> of <HI>I&s;rael</HI> and <HI>Judah,</HI> concluded his u&s;eful Life and Reign.</P>
<P>IN di&s;cour&s;ing upon which, I &s;hall offer &s;ome Con&s;iderations re&s;pecting the <HI>Nature, Cau&s;e,</HI> and <HI>A&s;pect</HI> of <HI>Death,</HI> upon the pre&s;ent and future Life; tending to repe&s;ent its Solemnity, and the Nece&s;&s;ity and Importance of Preparation for it, and &s;o proceed to the Improvement.</P>
<P>DEATH is the <HI>Di&s;&s;olution</HI> of the <HI>Union</HI> between Soul and Body, upon which our animal Life depends, and tho' we have no Rea&s;on to conclude, that the Life of our Soul is hereby annihilated; yet if we con&s;ider human Nature as compounded of Soul and Body, Death may be, in &s;ome Sen&s;e, &s;aid to be the vi&s;ible De&s;truction of it, becau&s;e it reduces all of Man, that is vi&s;ible, to deplorable Ruins! Reduces the active Creature full of anxious Thoughts, big
<PB N="6" REF="009023_0004_1030749C64488B30">
with great Projects and De&s;igns, and laborious in the Pur&s;uit of them, to a breathle&s;s Ma&s;s, a gha&s;tly Spectacle, devoid of Beauty and of Motion, which to prevent being offen&s;ive, mu&s;t &s;oon be hid in the dark and &s;ilent Retreat of the Grave, and become the Prey of Worms.</P>
<P>HOW this vital <HI>Union</HI> is di&s;&s;olved, we know no more than how it is formed; that Beings of &s;o va&s;tly different Natures as the Soul and Body are, &s;hould be clo&s;ely united is amazing, yet the Union appears to be as certain as it is a&s;toni&s;hing, from their Sympathy with, and Influence upon each other.</P>
<P>IN the mean Time this is apparent, that Death in its near Approaches, generally offers Violence to the Frame of Nature; tho' in &s;ome In&s;tances, the Lamp of Life expires gently and gradually, like a Candle in the Socket; yet, in mo&s;t, human Nature does not yield to the la&s;t Enemy without Reluctance, which as it manife&s;ts its deep Aver&s;ion to Death, &s;o it proves Death to be the Shipwreck of Nature: Our vital Parts being torn by the Violence of Di&s;ea&s;es, as a Ve&s;&s;el by the Rage of a Tempe&s;t, before it &s;inks into the Aby&s;s of the Grave!</P>
<P>BUT whence is it that Death puts a Period to our pre&s;ent Exi&s;tence, &s;hall we a&s;cribe this entirely to the &s;overeign Plea&s;ure of the &s;upreme Being, which without any regard to our Demerit, has &s;ubjected our Nature to &s;uch Mortality and Corruption? No! the &s;acred Scriptures a&s;&s;ert Death to be a <HI>penal Evil,</HI> i&s;&s;uing not from the meer Sovereignty, but the Ju&s;tice and Righteou&s;ne&s;s of God.</P>
<P>THO' Immortality was no Privilege that innocent Man could claim, by the original Right of his Nature; yet it was graciou&s;ly promi&s;ed as the Reward of his Obedience: It is
<PB N="7" REF="009023_0005_1030749EC0DC69C8">
true, the human Body was formed of the Du&s;t, and that this is not &s;o adapted to an immortal Life as the Soul, and therefore could only obtain and enjoy it by way of Gratuity, thro' the powerful Agency of a particular Providence.</P>
<P>THE Almighty to excite Man to Obedience, promi&s;ed this &s;upernatural Privilege, and to deter him from the Contrary, threatened Death as the Puni&s;hment of Sin: Which nece&s;&s;arily &s;uppo&s;es, that it would not have been his Lot, had he per&s;i&s;ted in his Obedience to his Creator and Sovereign: And hence the Apo&s;tle <HI>Paul</HI> a&s;&s;ures us, that <HI>The Wages of Sin is Death;</HI> and el&s;ewhere, that <HI>By one Man Sin entered into the World, and Death by Sin, and &s;o Death pa&s;&s;ed upon all Men, for that all had SINNED:</HI> How? Virtually, in their federal Head the fir&s;t <HI>Adam;</HI> it was therefore at this Door, that Death and all its preceeding Train of Di&s;ea&s;es and Mi&s;eries, has broke in upon and entirely inundated this lower World, whereby it is rendered a Vale of Tears, a Scene of Woe: And indeed it is congruous both to Rea&s;on and Ju&s;tice, that the Empire of Death and Mi&s;ery &s;hould be parallel in Extent with the Dominion of Sin, the one as univer&s;al as the other.</P>
<P>BUT what <HI>A&s;pect</HI> has this penal Evil, Death, upon the pre&s;ent Life? I an&s;wer, It may be &s;aid in general to be the End of it, it puts a final Period to the Drama of Life, whereby its &s;hifting Scenes are quite &s;hut up, and the Actors hurried off the Stage into a State of Inactivity and Darkne&s;s, ju&s;t as in the dead of the Night, an entire &s;top is put to all the Bu&s;ine&s;s of the preceeding Day, and every Place of public Concour&s;e wrapt up in &s;olemn Silence and Ob&s;curity!</P>
<P>BUT in particular, Death puts a Period to all our worldly <HI>Schemes</HI> and <HI>Labours,</HI> as well as to our <HI>&s;ecular</HI> State of <HI>Pro&s;perity</HI>
<PB N="8" REF="009023_0006_103074A245E22A20">
and <HI>Adver&s;ity,</HI> together with the Sea&s;ons of <HI>Grace,</HI> and Opportunities of <HI>Service.</HI></P>
<P>WHAT is &s;aid of <HI>Princes</HI> may be applied to <HI>Pea&s;ants,</HI> that <HI>Their Breath goeth out, and in that very Day their Thoughts peri&s;h:</HI> While the <HI>State&s;man</HI> is forming grand Projects, and imagines he has near compa&s;&s;ed his De&s;igns; Death, which con&s;tantly lies in Ambu&s;h, frequently, and &s;uddenly cru&s;hes his Schemes, di&s;appoints his Expectations, and bla&s;ts his Succe&s;s: Death carries all off from the Theatre of Action, to the Pri&s;on of the Grave, where tho&s;e, that a little while before, made a great Noi&s;e and Bu&s;tle, are locked up in a profound Sleep, out of which Nothing can awake them, but the loud Bla&s;t of the Archangel's Trumpet.</P>
<P>DEATH likewi&s;e puts a Period to our outward State, whether pro&s;perous or afflicted; it concludes Pro&s;perity by de&s;troying Life, the Foundation of it, and hurries the grande&s;t Potentates, from the Pomp of a Throne, to the Ob&s;curity of the Grave, where no Traces of their former Grandeur appear, in the gha&s;tly Remains of their Mortality, and the Places that knew them on Earth &s;hall know them no more.</P>
<P>ON the other Hand, Death concludes all the Evils of an afflicted State, this gives the Child of God a happy Di&s;charge from all the Hard&s;hips of the Chri&s;tian Warfare, and brings to a Period the Cruelty of Enemies, who&s;e Rage can pur&s;ue us no further than the Grave, <HI>There the Wicked cea&s;e from troubling, and the Weary are at Re&s;t:</HI> In a Word, Death is a &s;ecure Retreat from all the Calamities of Life, under the Pre&s;&s;ure of which the whole Creation groans and travels, and is therefore on this Account as acceptable to many, as the Darkne&s;s of the Night to the wearied Hireling!</P>
<P><PB N="9" REF="009023_0007_103074A4064047E0">BUT this is not all, Death likewi&s;e puts a final Period to all our Opportunities of Service; we have now many Advantages to do Good, and mu&s;t account for our Diligence and Fidelity in the Improvement of them; but the&s;e will &s;oon be over. Death will, in a little Time, bring every one of us that awful Me&s;&s;age, <HI>Give an Account of thy Steward&s;hip, for thou mayest be no longer Steward.</HI></P>
<P>BUT I proceed to con&s;ider the A&s;pect that Death has upon a <HI>future Life.</HI></P>
<P>HERE ob&s;erve, That by Death our Souls are brought to live in a State of Separation from our Bodies, tho' <HI>the Dust returns to</HI> its original <HI>Earth,</HI> yet our <HI>Spirits return to God who gave them.</HI> They become, by quitting the&s;e Man&s;ions, unembodied Spirits, and enter upon a new Scene of Life, in which they have no U&s;e for the Organs of Sen&s;e and Motion; Death liberates our Souls from the Incumbrance of elementary Bodies, and thereby awakes their noble Powers to greater Vigor and Sublimity in their Operations; it frees our Spirits from their Dependance on animal Bodies, and from the Impre&s;&s;ions made on them by &s;en&s;ible Objects, &s;o that the Plea&s;ures thence i&s;&s;uing for ever terminate, and are now derived from Objects better &s;uited to the immaterial Nature of the Soul. Further,</P>
<P>BY Death our Souls enter into an un&s;een World, and change their Place as well as their Mode of living, we pa&s;s by Death into the va&s;t HADES, or invi&s;ible World; to us an undi&s;covered and untried Country, which neither our Sen&s;es can give us any Notice of, or our Rea&s;on comprehend; and in which we &s;hall meet with new Society, and &s;uch a va&s;t Variety of new Objects and Entertainments, either in them&s;elves, or in Re&s;pect
<PB N="10" REF="009023_0008_103074AA7136F7F0">
of our <HI>Apprehen&s;ion</HI> of them; (then immediate and perfect) as will furni&s;h a &s;ufficient Fund for everla&s;ting Wonder, Love, and Prai&s;e! When our Spirits pa&s;s out of the narrow Current of Time, they leave this minute Point of Earth on which we tread, and take their Flight into tho&s;e immen&s;e Territories, over which he pre&s;ides who has the Keys of Hell and Death.</P>
<P>FURTHER, our Souls pa&s;s from a State of Tryal to a State of Rewards and Puni&s;hments, as incomprehen&s;ible as excellent, &s;atisfactory, eternal; Rewards which the human Mind in its &s;ublime&s;t Flights cannot gra&s;p, and which all Language and Images fail adequately to expre&s;s.</P>
<P>THO' the general Judgment be deferred till the Re&s;urrection, yet the Soul undergoes a particular Judgment, immediately after its Departure from the Body, or &s;omething analogous to it, which is previou&s;ly nece&s;&s;ary to its being fixed in a State of Bli&s;s or Mi&s;ery; and this the &s;acred Scriptures a&s;&s;ure us is the Ca&s;e of all that depart this Life, as appears by the Parable of <HI>Dives</HI> and <HI>Lazarus,</HI> the Promi&s;e of Chri&s;t to the Thief on the Cro&s;s, and the De&s;ire of the Apo&s;tle to be di&s;&s;olved, that he might be with Je&s;us.</P>
<P>THE <HI>Improvement</HI> of this Subject now calls for your Attention.</P>
<P>DOES DEATH bring &s;uch vi&s;ible Ruin upon our Nature, and is it the penal Fruit of Sin? Then what Rea&s;on has any Man living to be proud, who con&s;tantly carries about with him &s;uch poignant Incentives to Humility, in the Mortality of his very Frame, which has in it the Seeds of innumerable Di&s;ea&s;es, and of Death: Should he boa&s;t of his De&s;cent who mu&s;t <HI>&s;ay of Corruption thou art my Father, and to the Worm thou art my Mother and my Sister.</HI>&mdash;Shall we glory in our Strength
<PB N="11" REF="009023_0009_103074AC842C8310">
which is cru&s;hed before the Moth?&mdash;Or in our Beauty, who&s;e Features &s;hall put on a gha&s;tly Pale, and be &s;tained with Putrefaction?&mdash;Shall we be puffed up with Wealth and Honor who mu&s;t &s;o &s;oon leave them, and &s;ink in undi&s;tingui&s;hed Du&s;t and deep Oblivion?&mdash;And &s;eeing Sin has intailed this Cur&s;e of Mortality upon us, we may thence infer its great Malignity, and &s;hould be thereby enduced to behave towards it accordingly, as the mo&s;t odious Deformity and fatal Source of all our Woes!</P>
<P>IS the Empire of Death ab&s;olute and univer&s;al? Then how little is Man to be tru&s;ted in, who&s;e Breath is in his No&s;trils, continually expo&s;ed to innumerable Accidents? <HI>Surely Men of low Condition are Vanity, and Men of high Degree a Lye:</HI> Who may by corrupt Bia&s;es, incon&s;tant Re&s;olutions, or by &s;udden Death, di&s;appoint our Expectations from them; if any de&s;erved our Confidence, it would be the great and powerful, but even tho&s;e we are cautioned again&s;t a Dependance on: <HI>Trust not in Princes, nor in the Son of Man, in whom there is no Help, his Breath goeth out, he returns to his Earth; in that very Day his Thoughts peri&s;h.</HI></P>
<P>DOES Death put a Period to all our &s;ecular Affairs, then how moderate &s;hould we be in the Pro&s;ecution of them, inviolably ob&s;erving the rational and excellent Medium between Extreams, pre&s;cribed by the Apo&s;tle, <HI>Sorrowing as tho' we &s;orrowed not, and rejoicing as tho' we rejoiced not, becau&s;e the Fa&s;hion of this World pa&s;&s;eth away.</HI> Death &s;trips the World of its deceitful Charms, and repre&s;ents it in its native Dre&s;s of Emptine&s;s and Vanity; The Grave &s;ets before our Eyes in a &s;trong Point of Light, of how little Significancy human Greatne&s;s and Pro&s;perity are, to tho&s;e who mu&s;t in a &s;hort Space leave them all behind, and go as naked out of the World
<PB N="12" REF="009023_0010_103074AE40755710">
as they came into it: Certainly covetous Per&s;ons that make a great Noi&s;e and Bu&s;tle about their Projects and De&s;igns, <HI>Spend their Money for that which is not Bread, walk in a vain Shew, and vex them&s;elves in vain.</HI></P>
<P>WILL Death put a final Period to all the Sufferings of this Life and that to come, with Re&s;pect to &s;uch as fear God and work Righteou&s;ne&s;s? Then let us endure them with Patience and Fortitude, for they are <HI>light, and but for a Moment, and therefore not worthy to be compared with the exceeding great and eternal Weight of Glory before us!</HI> Death will &s;end our pained Bodies to the Dormitory of the Grave, and in Ca&s;e we truely repent of Sin, and believe in Je&s;us, tran&s;late our afflicted Souls to the Re&s;t of God, where all Tears &s;hall be wiped away, and we &s;hall enjoy a Felicity, large as our De&s;ires, and la&s;ting as our Souls.</P>
<P>AND &s;eeing Death concludes our gracious Sea&s;ons, and Opportunities of Service, let us <HI>awake out of Sleep,</HI> and <HI>work while the Day lasts, for the Night cometh in which no Man can work.</HI></P>
<P>BUT I proceed to &s;peak a little on the melancholy Occa&s;ion of this Di&s;cour&s;e, <HI>viz.</HI> The <HI>Death</HI> of our late gracious <HI>Soverign, King GEORGE</HI> the <HI>Second,</HI> of happy Memory; a Prince who may be in Ju&s;tice denominated, the <HI>Father</HI> of his People: A Prince who thro' the whole Cour&s;e of his Reign aimed at no de&s;potic tyrannical Sway, but on the Contrary expre&s;&s;ed due Re&s;pect to the repre&s;entative Body of the Nation, and made its Laws and Con&s;titution the invariable Rule of his Conduct: As he wronged no Man of his private <HI>Property,</HI> &s;o he granted to all that religious <HI>Liberty;</HI> which, as it is the Birth-right of all, &s;o it is the greate&s;t Support and Ornament
<PB N="13" REF="009023_0011_103074B014D69C28">
of real Chri&s;tianity, which is a rea&s;onable Service, founded on Argument, the I&s;&s;ue of impartial Enquiry and free Choice: But the Rever&s;e hereof, is built on the Ruins of every Thing that is valuable in human Nature, and directly tends to de&s;troy the Religion of Je&s;us entirely, by &s;etting up other Kings in his &s;piritual Kingdom, and claiming Allegiance to them in Oppo&s;ition to his Authority: In brief, it oppo&s;es Humanity and en&s;laves Mankind.</P>
<P>HERE give me Leave tran&s;iently to ob&s;erve, That there was a memorable Re&s;emblance or Analogy between the <HI>Hebrew</HI> Monarch <HI>David,</HI> and our decea&s;ed Sovereign, in Re&s;pect of his heroic military Character, as appears particularly from the intrepid Bravery of the latter at the famous Battle of DETTINGEN, the I&s;&s;ue of which reflected as great Glory on the Arms of <HI>Britain,</HI> as it did Scandal on tho&s;e of <HI>France!</HI></P>
<P>AS the Pro&s;perity of his People was the principal Object of his Attention, &s;o he was anxious and unwearied in the Pro&s;ecution of it to the la&s;t Moments of his Life; and hence the Nation's E&s;teem and Love encrea&s;ed with his growing Years, which is not only evident from their public Declarations, but likewi&s;e by their extraordinary <HI>Union</HI> among them&s;elves; and, that even under the prodigious Load of an expen&s;ive War, the great Variety of their Denominations, religious Principles, and Party Views notwith&s;tanding.</P>
<P>IN Con&s;equence of the afore&s;aid <HI>Union,</HI> it plea&s;ed that divine Providence, by which Kings reign, and Princes decree Ju&s;tice, to crown the latter Part of the Admini&s;tration of our decea&s;ed Sovereign with &s;uch an a&s;toni&s;hing Train of memorable Victories by Land and Sea, as will be the Wonder of Po&s;terity,
<PB N="14" REF="009023_0012_103074B32144C8E0">
and brighten the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Annals in all future Time: As this illu&s;trious Aera reflects great Honor on the King, his Councils, and Arms, &s;o if rightly improved, it opens, under Providence, a Pro&s;pect of EMPIRE for the Nation, beyond what the mo&s;t &s;anguine Hopes would have &s;ometime &s;ince dared to dictate; an Empire that will give her va&s;tly more Weight in the Scale of <HI>Europe,</HI> if not (in a Cour&s;e of Time) con&s;titute her the Arbitre&s;s of it.</P>
<P>BUT in the mid&s;t of this &s;urprizing Series of the mo&s;t important Events, in this critical Conjuncture of a War with numerous and potent Nations, combined in an unju&s;t, extraordinary and formidable Confederacy, to ruin entirely a Prote&s;tant Prince, and one of the mo&s;t renowned, intrepid, and invincible <HI>Heroes</HI> that the pre&s;ent or any pa&s;t Age has produced; I mean his <HI>Pru&s;&s;ian Majesty:</HI> In this Situation of Things our &s;ucce&s;sful Monarch dies, dies &s;uddenly, while beloved and revered, dies the De&s;ire and Delight of his People; while <HI>France,</HI> our artful implacable Enemy, who has &s;o long in&s;ulted the Honor, en&s;nared the Councils, and meditated the Ruin of our Nation: I &s;ay, while this arogant Rival-Power is exceedingly humbled, and almo&s;t brought to Rea&s;on, while <HI>France</HI> is &s;tripped of many Fortre&s;&s;es and va&s;t Domains in divers Parts of the World, e&s;pecially in <HI>America</HI> and the <HI>East-Indies;</HI> her Fleet broken, and her Trade de&s;troyed, our beloved Sovereign dies, and leaves his great and good De&s;igns, in Re&s;pect of War and Peace, on which his Heart was &s;o much &s;et, unfini&s;hed: A melancholy Providence this! which &s;hould be laid to Heart, and rightly improved; let us there|fore humble our&s;elves under the mighty Hand of God, that he may exalt us in due Time; let us implore Heaven that this Event may be over-ruled to the Good of our NATION in particular, and of ZION in general: Let us be hereby &s;tirred
<PB N="15" REF="009023_0013_103074B713D1DE28">
up to prepare for our own Di&s;&s;olution, which how near it is, and how &s;udden it may be, we know not; as <HI>Horace</HI> ju&s;tly ob&s;erves, Death makes no Di&s;tinction between the Cottages of Pea&s;ants and the Palaces of Princes:&mdash;And from hence let us likewi&s;e learn the extreme Vanity of all human Greatne&s;s and Dignity, which cannot &s;creen their Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ors from the Stroke of a &s;udden Death.</P>
<P>IN the mean Time give me Leave to ob&s;erve, that thro' divine Goodne&s;s, there are &s;ome Circum&s;tances attending this <HI>Gloom</HI> of Providence, which may allay our Griefs and animate our Hopes, e&s;pecially the&s;e following, <HI>viz.</HI> The MODE (or Circum&s;tances) of our late Sovereign's Exit, the Qualifications of his MINISTRY, the promi&s;ing Endowments of his SUCCESSOR, and the late famous VICTORY of the King of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> over the <HI>Austrian</HI> Army.</P>
<P>THE Circum&s;tances of our late Sovereign's Exit were re&s;pectable, &s;imilar to tho&s;e of the <HI>Hebrew</HI> Hero in our Text, particularly, he died in a good old Age, full of Days, being arrived to his Seventy-&s;eventh Year, after a Reign of Thirty-three, very near the &s;ame Space that <HI>David</HI> reigned over <HI>Jeru&s;alem;</HI> it is but a &s;mall Number of Mankind of any Order that live to &s;uch an Age, and very few Princes in any Part of the World reign &s;o long a Space. Certainly, my Brethren, we have great Rea&s;on to adore the ble&s;&s;ed God, with the mo&s;t ardent Gratitude, that &s;o mild and equitable an Admini&s;tration was continued with us &s;o long; which if compared with the arbitrary, popi&s;h, oppre&s;&s;ive Reigns of the Male Line of the STEWART Family, may in Rea&s;on accent the Gratitude of all &s;incere Prote&s;tants, for &s;o very valuable a Mercy.</P>
<P><PB N="16" REF="009023_0014_103074BA63483A00">BUT to proceed, our late Sovereign likewi&s;e died full of Riches and Honor, the Legacies mentioned in his la&s;t Will prove the former, and the numerous Addre&s;&s;es of the Nation confirm the latter, and both of them are valuable Benefits, promi&s;ed by the Almighty, to excite the Creatures Obedience.</P>
<P>IT is likewi&s;e an encouraging Circum&s;tance, that our decea&s;ed Sovereign left &s;o able, faithful, and re&s;olute a <HI>Ministry</HI> at the Helm of the Nation; among which the truly Honorable Mr. PITT &s;hines with di&s;tingui&s;hed Lu&s;tre, a PATRIOT of &s;uch &s;urprizing Capacity, &s;uch extraordinary Di&s;intere&s;tedne&s;s, and un&s;haken Firmne&s;s, as no Artifice could elude, no Oppo&s;ition intimidate, or Bribe &s;educe, from his inviolable Adherence to &s;uch Mea&s;ures as were nece&s;&s;ary to promote the Honor and Intere&s;t of the Nation; a Patriot this, who is, in very Deed, the Guardian, Joy, and Glory of his Country: It is he who has rou&s;ed the &s;leeping Genius of the Nation from a State of inglorious Ea&s;e, &s;ordid Pu&s;illanimity, and &s;orry Congre&s;&s;es, to War and Arms, to a&s;&s;ert its ju&s;t Rights by numerous Acts of heroic Bravery, whereby the Honor of the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> FLAG and Land Forces is retrieved, vindicated from Contempt, made re&s;pectable in the E&s;teem of all Nations, made the Joy of its Friends, and the Terror of its Enemies: The&s;e glorious De&s;igns were &s;o far from being compa&s;&s;ed by the &s;pecious pacific Schemes and trifling Treaties, (with a Court inured to Artifice and Chicane) which were propo&s;ed and pur&s;ued by a former Mini&s;try, that the Honor and Intere&s;t of the Nation were betrayed, its Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ions, Trade, and Influence, by Degrees &s;o impaired, that it was brought to the very Brink of Ruin, a Plan to complete it was as artfully as confidently concerted, and almo&s;t fully prepared for the fatal Execution: O dreadful, deplorable Situation! <HI>(Quis talia fando, temperet a Lachrymis;)</HI>
<PB N="17" REF="009023_0015_103074BFF697B158">
But ble&s;&s;ed be God, thro' the favorable Smiles of Providence upon the Conduct of a &s;kilful, faithful PILOT, the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Ve&s;&s;el almo&s;t &s;hipwrecked, now emerges above the threatning Waves, re&s;umes its ancient Empire, and commands the Ocean.</P>
<P>'TIS He that has directed the Nation to its true and mo&s;t important Intere&s;t, as well as to the mo&s;t probable and lea&s;t expen&s;ive Mea&s;ures to obtain and pre&s;erve it, by annexing to the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Crown, thro' a proper Exertion of its chief natural Strength (its &s;uperior naval Force) this We&s;tern EMPIRE, of va&s;t, yea, unknown Extent, and of immen&s;e Value.</P>
<P>AND it mu&s;t needs give &s;en&s;ible Plea&s;ure to every generous Mind, to &s;ee the extraordinary Merit of this Gentleman, &s;o publicly, &s;o ju&s;tly, and generally acknowledged by the Nation, in Sentiments and Expre&s;&s;ions of the mo&s;t pa&s;&s;ionate and per|manent Gratitude, hereby nobly laboring to make the Memory of his valuable Services as la&s;ting as Time it&s;elf, as durable as they are diffu&s;ive and truly noble: A Reward, which tho' it be mo&s;t rea&s;onable and equitable, yet becau&s;e of the prodigious Degeneracy of human Nature, is not always the Attendant of the mo&s;t noble Actions, the mo&s;t di&s;tingui&s;hed Merit, witne&s;s famous MARLBOROUGH, ju&s;tly for &s;ome Time the Darling and Pride of the Nation, the Wonder of <HI>Eu|rope,</HI> and the Scourge of <HI>France,</HI> yet afterwards, as unju&s;tly as ungratefully, reproached, rejected, and contemned: O La|mentable! may that unhappy Fate be graciou&s;ly prevented in the pre&s;ent Ca&s;e, by that Providence that pre&s;ides over all!</P>
<P>BUT that which is &s;till more animating in our pre&s;ent Situation, is the amiable <HI>Character</HI> we have received of his pre&s;ent Maje&s;ty, <HI>King</HI> GEORGE <HI>the Third,</HI> the Grand&s;on of
<PB N="18" REF="009023_0016_103074C2CBCE1070">
our decea&s;ed Sovereign, <HI>who now reigns in his Stead,</HI> a <HI>Character</HI> which his early In&s;truction in the Principles of LIBERTY, enforced by the amiable Examples of his famous Predece&s;&s;ors and Relatives, &s;ince the ever memorable <HI>Revolution,</HI> under pious <HI>King William,</HI> of glorious Memory; King WILLIAM, who in the mid&s;t of much Labor, eminent Hazard, and great Di&s;couragements, nobly laid, with a ma&s;terly Hand, the very Foundations of all that is dear to us, as Men, as Chri&s;tians, and as Prote&s;tants; LAID the Ba&s;is of all our pre&s;ent ine&s;timable Privileges of every Kind, Privileges that &s;hould form &s;uch indelible Impre&s;&s;ions of Gratitude upon our Minds, as no artful Colorings of de&s;igning Men, or length of Time, &s;hould ever be able to extingui&s;h.</P>
<P>BUT to return from this Digre&s;&s;ion, what has been &s;aid concerning the reigning Prince, con&s;idered in Connection with his religious and virtuous EDUCATION in Prote&s;tant Prin|ciples, enforced by good Practice <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">Precepta docent, Exempla cogunt.</NOTE> (under the Tuition of a Nobleman of di&s;tingui&s;hed Piety, a Preceptor of &s;uperior Ge|nius) and recommended by the Influence of his religious and illu&s;trious Parent, the PRINCESS DOWAGER of WALES, renders the afore&s;aid <HI>Character</HI> highly probable, and gives us Rea&s;on to hope, that his tender opening Mind has been early imbued with tho&s;e noble and humane Sentiments, early impre&s;&s;ed with tho&s;e devout Affections, which when habitual and prevalent, are the true Genius and di&s;tingui&s;hing Glory of vital Chri&s;ti|anity, as nece&s;&s;ary, as ornamental, nece&s;&s;ary both to private and public Life, for every Step of Elevation in the Scale of Offices, Dignity and Dominion, from the lowe&s;t to the highe&s;t of them (from the Nadir to the Zenith) to make them comfortable, honorable, and u&s;eful here, and to make us meet for a future glorious State!</P>
<P><PB N="19" REF="009023_0017_103074C58F3599B8">I MAY add, that the preceeding CHARACTER of his pre&s;ent Maje&s;ty is confirmed by the Beginnings of his Admini&s;tration, e&s;pecially by the PROCLAMATION for the Encouragement of Virtue and Piety, and for preventing and puni&s;hing Vice, Prophane&s;s and Immorality; a PROCLAMA|TION worthy of the greate&s;t and be&s;t of Princes; a PROCLA|MATION as nece&s;&s;ary in the&s;e Times of Degeneracy and Corruption, to promote the Safety and Weal of the Nation, as it is excellent in Re&s;pect of its Matter, and elegant in Regard of its Form; the &s;trong Terms in which it is expre&s;&s;ed, together with the Order to read it publicly in Courts and Churches &s;everal Times a Year, have an excellent Tendency, a pious and promi&s;ing A&s;pect on the Church and Nation, and are an encouraging OMEN of Good to come.</P>
<P>HEAR with Attention, Veneration, and grateful Love, what his gracious Maje&s;ty, our young SOLOMON, our <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> JOSIAS, &s;peaks from the THRONE!</P>
<LETTER>
<OPENER><SIGNED>GEORGE <HI>Rex,</HI></SIGNED></OPENER>
<P>We mo&s;t &s;eriou&s;ly and religiou&s;ly con&s;idering, that it is an indi&s;pen&s;able Duty on Us to be careful above all other Things, to pre&s;erve and advance the Honor and Service of Almighty God, and to di&s;courage and &s;uppre&s;s all Vice, Prophane&s;s, Debauchery, and Immorality, which are &s;o high|ly di&s;plea&s;ing to God, &s;o great a Reproach to our Religion and Government, and by Means of the frequent ill Examples of the Practices thereof, have &s;o fatal a Tendency to the Corruption of many of our loving Subjects, otherwi&s;e religiou&s;ly and virtuou&s;ly di&s;po&s;ed, and which (if not timely remedied) may ju&s;tly draw down the divine Vengeance on Us and our Kingdom: We al&s;o, humbly acknowledging,
<PB N="20" REF="009023_0018_103074C9ACE898E8">
that we cannot expect the Ble&s;&s;ing and Goodne&s;s of Almighty God (by whom Kings reign, and on which we entirely rely) to make our Reign happy and pro&s;perous to our&s;elf and our People, without a religious Ob&s;ervance of God's holy Laws: To the Intent therefore, that Religion, Piety, and good Manners may (according to our mo&s;t hearty De&s;ire) flouri&s;h and encrea&s;e under our Admini&s;tration and Govern|ment, we have thought fit, by the Advice of our Privy-Council, to i&s;&s;ue this our Royal Proclamation, and do hereby declare our Royal Purpo&s;e and Re&s;olution, to di&s;|countenance and puni&s;h all Manner of Vice, Prophane&s;s and Immorality, in all Per&s;ons, of what&s;oever Degree or Quality, within this our Realm, and particularly, in &s;uch as are employed near our Royal Per&s;on; and that for the Encouragement of Religion and Morality, we will upon all Occa&s;ions di&s;tingui&s;h Per&s;ons of Piety and Virtue, by Marks of our Royal Favor. And we do expect and require that all Per&s;ons of Honor, or in Place of Authority, will give good Example by their own Virtue and Piety, and to their utmo&s;t contribute to the di&s;countenancing Per&s;ons of di&s;&s;olute and debauched Lives: And we do hereby &s;trictly enjoin and prohibit all our loving Subjects, of what Degree or Quality &s;oever, from playing on the Lord's Day, at Dice, Cards, or any other Game what&s;oever, either in public or private Hou&s;es, or other Place or Places what&s;oever: And we do hereby require and command them, and every of them, decently and reverently, to attend the Wor&s;hip of God on every Lord's Day, on Pain of our highe&s;t Di&s;plea&s;ure, and of being proceeded again&s;t with the utmo&s;t Rigor that may be by Law.&mdash;Thus far the KING.</P>
</LETTER>
<P>HOW va&s;tly different is this Specimen from that execrable Order, to read a <HI>Book</HI> of <HI>Sports</HI> on the Lord's Day, which &s;ome
<PB N="21" REF="009023_0019_103074CB6631A620">
Time &s;ince came from the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> THRONE; <HI>(O Tempora, O Mores!)</HI> I &s;ay the THRONE; but influenced by an infamous PRELATE, who was as great a Cur&s;e to the NATION, as he was a Reproach to tho&s;e of his own Order, a popi&s;hly inclined CEREMONY-MONGER, who crammed down the Throat of the NATION by meer Force, not of Argument, but of civil Power, the pernicious Principles of ARMINIUS, before oppo&s;ed by the Generality of the CLERGY, as well as openly and expre&s;ly di&s;|claimed and dete&s;ted by the PARLIAMENT, its repre&s;entative Body, as the direct Road to POPERY; but have ever &s;ince be|come prevalent in it <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">I mean by the Word IT, the Nation.</NOTE> among Per&s;ons of every Order: When I con&s;ider the per&s;ecuting Conduct of this Man in general, and in particular the BOOK of SPORTS procured by him, to be read by all the Mini&s;ters of the Churches on the Lord's Day, pub|licly, on Pain of Exclu&s;ion from their Office and Support, I cannot help thinking on that horrid Purpo&s;e of the PAGAN, which I tremble to relate. <HI>(Horre&s;co referens.)</HI>
<Q>Flectere &s;i nequeo Superos, Acheronta movebo.</Q>
<HI>i. e.</HI> If I cannot incline the Diety to favor my De&s;igns, I will try what A&s;&s;i&s;tance I can get from the Devil.&mdash;I will not pre&s;ume to &s;ay that his GRACE had any Thoughts of Satan, or knowingly harboured any bad Intentions in his &s;evere and prophane Management; no Doubt he imagined that he did God Service by it, which doubtle&s;s le&s;&s;ened the Degree of its Malignity in Re&s;pect of him&s;elf, but in the Mean Time, his Practice was certainly worthy of the wor&s;t of Sentiments and De&s;igns; and in Regard of Matter, Tendency, and I&s;&s;ue (as to others) the &s;ame as if his had been &s;uch.</P>
<P>IT is therefore unaccountable that any who wear a human Form, &s;hould pretend to vindicate &s;uch horrid Iniquity in open
<PB N="22" REF="009023_0020_103074CE25F95810">
Day, but the&s;e <HI>Men,</HI> if we may venture to call them &s;uch, who &s;carce retain any Thing human but the Shape, glory in their Shame, and while they profe&s;s them&s;elves wi&s;e become Fools; as they bewray awful Enmity again&s;t all Religion and Virtue, and hereby commence Enemies to Mankind, and public Pe&s;ts to civil Society; &s;o they, with equal Wi&s;dom and Mode&s;ty, &s;et them&s;elves in Oppo&s;ition again&s;t, and bid open Defiance to, the plaine&s;t Dictates of Rea&s;on and common Sen&s;e: Tell it not in <HI>Gath,</HI> and publi&s;h it not in the Streets of <HI>A&s;kelon,</HI> that any Prote&s;tant has done this, lea&s;t the Uncircum|ci&s;ed triumph; be a&s;toni&s;hed, O ye Heavens, at this crim&s;on Impiety, and be horribly afraid!</P>
<P>BUT, ble&s;&s;ed be JEHOVAH, we live in better Times, having the un&s;peakably precious and important Privilege of a truly PIOUS PRINCE on the THRONE, who may, with Ju&s;tice and Propriety, be compared to King SOLOMON, in Re&s;pect of Wi&s;dom and Prudence as to the Affairs of Government and State, and to King JOSIAS in Regard of Humility, Mode&s;ty, early and noble Zeal for Religion and Virtue, &s;o far as he has yet proceeded in his ADMINISTRATION, in which the&s;e excellent Virtues and princely Endowments &s;hine with &s;uch rival Lu&s;tre, that its hard to &s;ay which has the Preheminence: This real and reviving Verity appears with a &s;trong Glare of Light, from all the Tran&s;actions of his infant Reign, whether con&s;i|dered &s;ingly, or in a complex View, and e&s;pecially from the PROCLAMATION (before mentioned) and his SPEECH to both Hou&s;es of <HI>Parliament,</HI> which ea&s;ily and evidently appear to every unprejudiced Mind, to be no Matter of Form, Cu&s;tom, or Compliment, but a candid, cordial Declaration, a deter|mined Re&s;olution, and &s;erious Endeavour to promote the Honor of God and the Good of the Nation, by the U&s;e of tho&s;e Means which Revelation pre&s;cribes, and Rea&s;on it&s;elf
<PB N="23" REF="009023_0021_103074D22188BB68">
confirms; Means that only can, under Providence, &s;ecure and perpetuate the Pro&s;perity of any Nation, witne&s;s the four famous Monarchies, and the <HI>Jewi&s;h</HI> Kingdom, who for the Neglect of them were brought to extreme Di&s;tre&s;s and deplorable Ruin! The&s;e Specimens appear to proceed from a rational con&s;i&s;tent View of Things, and from a Heart tenderly touched, and inten&s;ely engaged.</P>
<P>AS the Royal Writings (before mentioned) in Favor of Religion and Liberty, are at lea&s;t equal to any that ever came from the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> Throne in any preceeding Period, in Re&s;pect of their important Matter, nervous Force of Argument, and inimitable Beauty of Diction, as well as on Account of the &s;uperior Acumen, di&s;tingui&s;hed Candor, Mode&s;ty and Affection with which they are formed; &s;o it is hoped they cannot fail of giving the highe&s;t Satisfaction to every Man, that fears God and loves his Country, in every Part of the <HI>Briti&s;h</HI> EMPIRE, and of exciting their Affection to their Sovereign, as well as their Gratitude to GOD, on Account of this animating Pro&s;pect of national Weal, Pro&s;perity and Glory, in all valuable Re&s;pects, as well as the be&s;t Intere&s;t of Individuals, which thro' the gracious Agency of his all-ruling Providence, now opens before us!</P>
<P>BUT to give Light and Force to this Argument, I mu&s;t beg Leave, with all the Veneration and Re&s;pect due from a Subject to his Sovereign, to borrow a few Hints from the afore&s;aid <HI>Speech</HI> of his SACRED MAJESTY, to both Hou&s;es of PARLIAMENT, which are as follows:</P>
<LETTER>
<OPENER><SALUTE>My Lords and Gentlemen,</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>I need not tell you the Addition of Weight which im|mediately falls upon me, in being called to the Government
<PB N="24" REF="009023_0022_103074D5B74619C8">
of this free and powerful Country at &s;uch a Time, and under &s;uch Circum&s;tances. My Con&s;olation is the Upright|ne&s;s of my own Intentions, your faithful and united A&s;&s;i&s;tance, and the Ble&s;&s;ing of Heaven upon our joint En|deavours, which I devoutly implore.</P>
<P>BORN and educated in this Country, I glory in the Name of <HI>Briton;</HI> and the peculiar Happine&s;s of my Life will ever con&s;i&s;t in promoting the Welfare of a People who&s;e Loyalty and warm Affection to me, I con&s;ider as the greate&s;t and mo&s;t permanent Security of my Throne: And I doubt not but their Steadine&s;s in tho&s;e Principles, will equal the Firmne&s;s of my invariable Re&s;olution to adhere to, and &s;trengthen this excellent Con&s;titution in Church and State, and to maintain the Toleration inviolable. The civil and religious Rights of my loving Subjects are equally dear to me, with the mo&s;t valuable Prerogatives of my Crown; and as the &s;ure&s;t Foundation of the whole, and the be&s;t Means to draw down the divine Favor on my Reign, it is my fixed Purpo&s;e to countenance and encourage the Practice of true Religion and <HI>Virtue.</HI></P>
<P><HI>My Lords and Gentlemen,</HI></P>
<P>THE Eyes of all <HI>Europe</HI> are upon you, from your Re&s;o|lutions, the Prote&s;tant Intere&s;t hopes for Protection.&mdash;</P>
</LETTER>
<P>AS this and the other Performance (before mentioned) of our PIOUS Sovereign, <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">As I Tru&s;t.</NOTE> need no Commendation from any, &s;o I freely acknowledge they are va&s;tly above mine, yet I hope I may be indulged the Plea&s;ure of expre&s;&s;ing the genuine Sen|timents of my Heart on &s;o agreeable, yea glorious an Occa&s;ion,
<PB N="25" REF="009023_0023_103074DB0B141710">
which promi&s;es &s;o great Good to the Church and State: O may the gracious God make us deeply &s;en&s;ible of the un|&s;peakable Moment of our pre&s;ent Advantages, both religious and civil, and enable us to te&s;tify our Gratitude to God and Man for them, by a con&s;cientious Improvement; <HI>giving to Cae&s;ar the Things that are Cae&s;ar's, and to God the Things that are God's;</HI> and may our gracious Sovereign, who begins his Reign with &s;uch amiable Au&s;pices of MODESTY, PRUDENCE, and PIETY, live long a Comfort to him&s;elf, a Ble&s;&s;ing to the Kingdoms, over which he governs in particular, and to the Prote&s;tant Church in general; may he be in Fact, what by his Royal Dignity he is in Title, <HI>a Defender of the Faith,</HI> and this I verily hope will be the honorable and happy Attendant of his Reign; <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot"><P>THE great Influence of <HI>Authority</HI> properly exerted, and enforced by good <HI>Example</HI> from the THRONE, to promote national REFORMATION, and the Power of the Contrary to corrupt and deprave Communities, appear in Contra&s;t with &s;ufficient Light and Evidence from the Narrative given in the &s;acred Pages re&s;pecting the KINGS of JUDAH and ISRAEL.</P>
<P>AND the Nece&s;&s;ity of a national REFORMATION to &s;ecure and perpetuate national Pro&s;perity and Glory, appears not only from expre&s;s and repeated <HI>Promi&s;es</HI> thereof in this Situation of Things, and as explicite <HI>Threatnings</HI> of the Contrary in Ca&s;e of a general Corruption of Manners; (<HI>See Jer.</HI> xviii. 7&mdash;11&mdash;) but al&s;o from the Series of God's dealings with the People of <HI>I&s;rael,</HI> and other Nations in Conformity thereto.&mdash;This divine Conduct Rea&s;on it&s;elf approves, for &s;eeing it is but right, ju&s;t, and condecent, &s;uitable to the divine Character, &s;uitable to the very Nature of Things, and nece&s;&s;ary to an&s;wer the Ends of Government; that the moral Governor of the World &s;hould di&s;countenance Vice, and encourage Virtue, by proper Puni&s;hments and Rewards: And &s;eeing Communities, as &s;uch, terminate with the pre&s;ent Life, of Con&s;equence the Members that compo&s;e them can only be treated as Individuals in a future State, it is therefore nece&s;&s;ary that BODIES POLITIC, he rewarded or puni&s;hed here according to their public MORAL CHARACTER.&mdash; Some Peculiarities of the <HI>Jewi&s;h</HI> State (under a Theocracy) in juridicial Matters, adapted to their &s;ingular Circum&s;tances, do not in any Mea&s;ure militate again&s;t, or enervate Arguments deduced from Rea&s;on and Equity, which equally affect all Nations in all Ca&s;es that are &s;imilar and parallel; and hence the ab&s;olute Nece&s;&s;ity of a general REFORMATION of Manners, to promote national Weal and Pro&s;pe|rity, and prevent De&s;olation and Ruin, is con&s;picuous and apparent: Without this, no political PENETRATION, no martial FORTITUDE, however nece&s;&s;ary and amiable, no SUCCESSES, tho' numerous and glorious, no NAVAL ARMAMENTS and <HI>Land Forces,</HI> however grand and formidable, no OPPULENCE, however immen&s;e, can &s;ecure guilty Nations from Mi&s;ery and Ruin, denounced by incen&s;ed Omnipotence, any more than dry Stubble can defend it&s;elf in Conte&s;t with devour|ing Flames!</P></NOTE> But to &s;um up the De&s;ire of my Heart in
<PB N="26" REF="009023_0024_103074DF453DA4F0">
one Word, give me Leave to &s;ay, <HI>God Save the King;</HI> or, which is the &s;ame in other Words, in a different Language, a little paraphra&s;ed:
<Q><L>"Unum opto id, Princeps &s;it tibi certa Salus:</L>
<L>"Hoc &s;atis unum: quoniam te So&s;pite nobis,</L>
<L>"Succedent Regno pro&s;pera cuneta tuo.</L>
<L>"Caltha &s;uos nu&s;quam Vultus a Sole reflectit,</L>
<L>"Illo oriente patens, illo abeunte latens,</L>
<L>"Nos quoque pendemus de te Sal noster, ad omnes</L>
<L>"Expo&s;iti rerum te &s;ubeunte vices.</L></Q></P>
<P>IN fine, when the State of the War in <HI>Germany</HI> very lately took an unpromi&s;ing Turn, by the <HI>Ru&s;&s;ian</HI> and <HI>Austrian</HI> Armies taking the <HI>Capital</HI> of <HI>Pru&s;&s;ia,</HI> and by the Defeat of the He|reditary <HI>Prince</HI> of <HI>Brun&s;wick</HI> by the <HI>French,</HI> and every Thing looked dark and di&s;tre&s;&s;ing; then did divine Providence, when all was put to the Ri&s;que, &s;ea&s;onably and graciou&s;ly interpo&s;e in our Favor, by giving a complete and deci&s;ive Victory over the Grand <HI>Austrian</HI> Army, under the Direction of Mar&s;hal DAUN, to the brave, but oppre&s;&s;ed and invironed KING of PRUSSIA.</P>
<P>THIS Victory appears the more marvellous, affecting, and important, when we con&s;ider the Superiority of the <HI>Austrian</HI> Army, in Re&s;pect of their Numbers, the Fre&s;hne&s;s of their Troops, their Advantage in Re&s;pect of Situation, and the great Experience, Skill, and Caution of their General, another
<PB N="27" REF="009023_0025_103074E1323BB5F0">
FABIUS MAXIMUS, <NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">The <HI>Roman</HI> General who conquered HANNIBAL, the <HI>Carthaginian,</HI> by Delays.</NOTE> who having great Re&s;ources, has long &s;ought by Delays to ruin his <HI>Pru&s;&s;ian</HI> Maje&s;ty, and had got con&s;i|derable Advantage again&s;t him in two preceeding Battles, &s;ome Time ago, which mu&s;t give fre&s;h Spirit to his Forces; and on the other Hand, when we at the &s;ame Time view our brave Allie under very di&s;couraging Circum&s;tances, his Troops fatigued, deprived of many of his experienced gallant Generals, and faith|ful Veteran Soldiers, in former bloody Battles, who in Firmne&s;s equaled the <HI>Macedonian</HI> PHALANX, him&s;elf oppre&s;&s;ed with the Weight of an unequal War, at a Lo&s;s which Way to bend his Cour&s;e, or which of his numerous and potent Enemies to fight fir&s;t; add to this that the End of the Campaign was near, and that he had no Re&s;ource (no &s;ufficient one) in Ca&s;e of a total Defeat, from hence I pre&s;ume it appears, that his Fate and ours turned in &s;ome Mea&s;ure on the I&s;&s;ue of this BATTLE; there was a Danger either of his lo&s;ing his Crown, or our loo&s;ing our late Acqui&s;itions to pre&s;erve it: How great then is the Goodne&s;s of God in crowning the Scene thus far by this &s;urprizing Succe&s;s, when there was a Nece&s;&s;ity of putting all to the Fortune of War upon &s;uch unequal Terms, to prevent a &s;ure but lingring Death: Surely this gives Encou|ragement to expect the Continuance of the divine Favors, in Ca&s;e we faithfully improve, by Repentance and Reformation, the Mercies we have already received, and re&s;olutely pro&s;ecute the &s;ame political and martial Mea&s;ures (to which many &s;incere Friends of the Nation, heartily wi&s;h the Addition of another Allie at lea&s;t, to a&s;&s;i&s;t in the Land War, in Ca&s;e the Peace is not concluded this Winter) which have been hitherto favored by Providence, which may the good God grant for Je&s;us Chri&s;t his Sake. <HI>Amen, Amen.</HI></P>
